== Region Population ==

<div style="position:absolute; top:5%; left:5%;">

Components of Population Change: Region


</div>
[[File:data:image/png;base64,]]

The central Puget Sound region continued to grow despite a global pandemic in 2020. The pandemic affected the rate of change for both natural population increase as well as increases due to migration.<br />
<br />
<br />


<div style="float: left; width: 30%;">

* The four counties added approximately 39,000 people in 2020
* The last time the region added under 50,000 people in a year was 2013
* Growth was equally divided between Migration and Natural changes in 2020 - a noticeable difference from the past seven years


</div>

== Region Jobs Total ==

<div style="position:absolute; top:5%; left:5%;">

Wage &amp; Salary Employment: Region Total


</div>
[[File:data:image/png;base64,]]

Employment in the central Puget Sound region continues to recover from the impacts of the global pandemic.<br />
<br />
<br />


<div style="float: left; width: 30%;">

* In May of 2020 at the height of the pandemic job losses, regional employment was 1.95M - a level of employment last seen in the region in 2014
* In May of 2021, regional employment was 2.1M - still below 2019 and similar to employment levels in 2017


</div>

== Unemployment Changes ==

<div style="position:absolute; top:5%; left:5%;">

Unemployment Claims: Initial Claims


</div>
[[File:data:image/png;base64,]]

Initial Weekly unemployment claims have hovered near 10k a week in the spring of 2021 - still more than double what they were in late 2019 and early 2020 but far below the 30k per week averages from the spring of 2020.<br />

== Unemployment by Race ==

<div style="position:absolute; top:5%; left:5%;">

Unemployment Claims: Continuing Claims by Race


</div>
[[File:data:image/png;base64,]]

Unemployment rates continue to vary by race/ethnicity. Early in the pandemic, the unemployment rate were over 17% for African American workers. By June of 2021, the unemployment rate for African American workers was 3.5%, far lower than early in the pandemic but still over twice the rate for White workers (1.5%). Native Hawaiian/Pacific Islanders had the highest unemployment in June 2021 of approximately 5%.<br />
<br />
<br />

== Ferry ==

<div style="position:absolute; top:5%; left:5%;">

Ferry Ridership: WSF Routes serving the PSRC Region


</div>
[[File:data:image/png;base64,]]

Overall ridership on Ferry routes operated by WSF in the PSRC region for the first seven months of 2021 is 69% of the total ridership from 2019. The Bremerton to Seattle and Bainbridge Island to Seattle routes continue to have the greatest drop in ridership compared to 2019, a reflection of the commuter nature of those routes.<br />
